%N A390355 Maximum number of vertices that ever have chips in a layer in a certain chip-firing game that starts with 2^n chips and is described in the comments.
%C A390355 Consider the following chip-firing game on the integer points of the first quadrant (i.e., set of vertices (x, y) where x and y are nonnegative integers): start with 2^n chips at the origin (i.e., point (0, 0)). If a vertex (x, y) has at least 2 chips, it fires by sending one chip to (x+1, y) and one chip to (x, y+1). The vertex (x, y) loses two chips during each firing. The total number of firings in the game is finite. For each nonnegative integer i, we define layer i to be the set of all vertices that have Manhattan distance i from the origin. The term a(n) is the maximum number of vertices in a layer that ever have chips.
%C A390355 The vertices in one layer that ever have chips form a contiguous segment.
%C A390355 Below, we have a table for the maximum number of chips at each vertex in the firing process for n=4:
%C A390355       16
%C A390355      8 8
%C A390355     4 8 4
%C A390355    2 6 6 2
%C A390355   1 4 6 4 1
%C A390355    2 5 5 2
%C A390355   1 3 4 3 1
%C A390355    1 3 3 1
%C A390355     1 2 1
%C A390355      1 1
%H A390355 Ryota Inagaki, Tanya Khovanova, and Austin Luo, <a href="https://arxiv.org/abs/2601.09125">Chip-firing on the Lattice of Nonnegative Integer Points</a>, arXiv:2601.09125 [math.CO], 2026. See p. 11.
%H A390355 Wikipedia, <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Chip-firing_game">Chip-firing game</a>.
%e A390355 In the example in the comments for n=4, the longest row has 5 elements. Thus, a(4) = 5.
%o A390355 (Python)
%o A390355 def longestRow_Length(n):
%o A390355     l1 = [2**n]
%o A390355     stab = (max(l1) <= 1)
%o A390355     largest = 1
%o A390355     row_count=1
%o A390355     while not stab:
%o A390355         l2 = [l1[0]//2]
%o A390355         for i in range(1, len(l1)):
%o A390355             l2.append(l1[i]//2 + l1[i-1]//2)
%o A390355         l2.append(l1[len(l1)-1]//2)
%o A390355         l1 = l2
%o A390355         stab = (max(l1) <= 1)
%o A390355         if l1[0] == 0:
%o A390355             l1 = l1[1:]
%o A390355         if l1[-1] == 0:
%o A390355             l1 = l1[:len(l1)-1]
%o A390355         largest = max(largest, len(l1))
%o A390355     return largest
%o A390355 s = ""
%o A390355 for n in range(27):
%o A390355     s = s + str(longestRow_Length(n)) +", "
%o A390355 print(s)
